column49: I really can't set my own due dates??  I didn't realize such a big change had been made.  I did notice that the flyers looked a bit different when I sent them home at the end of last week and there wasn't going to be an option for ordering through me which I wasn't too disappointed in but also thought it was a little strange.  Most parents in the past few years had started ordering online but there was a family every once in a while that didn't want to order online or had such a small order that they would just send me the few dollars in cash.  I decided to get on today to check on my account and start my teacher order and noticed that the due date was set and I couldn't change it.  As a teacher that has used Scholastic for many years I was kind of shocked to see such a change.  Also the prices (which I understand with the economy and everything) have just gone up a lot.

column49: I have ordered books from Scholastic Book Clubs for over 30 years and I have always given you a very good rating, but the prices of these books are outrageous!  I have bought over 2,000 books from you and always encouraged my parents to buy from you because you would always beat the prices of the same books in a book store.  I hope your books have better prices for the rest of the year and I hope I can receive my Early Childhood book flyers again.  I will not recommend Scholastic Book Clubs to teachers or my parents until you bring back the fun paperbacks that cost under $5.00. I hope I have explained my displeasure and low ratings for right now. I also hope I can give feedback again this year with a different outcome.

column49: Family Order Due Date- I don't like that I cannot pick the due date. In months with holidays, I set the due date early in the month so that students have their books to enjoy all month long (example-  in October, I like to have orders due by the first week so that they can have their Halloween books for a couple weeks before  Halloween.  Same thing with winter holidays and Christmas. What happens if the book order arrives while we are on our Winter Break? Then they have to wait til January to receive their books.    I'm sure this change was well intended to help us teachers have 1 less thing on our plate to manage, but I miss having the control of the due date.      I'm curious if  you will go back to giving us the due date choice. Thank you.

column41: View/edit account information
column49: The navigation on this site is very convoluted.  There's way too many clicks involved to get info.  There should be shortcut buttons on the main page.  Example:  I wanted to see the balance on the accounts for my kids.  I never did figure out how to get to this info.  I used FAQ's, thought I followed the directions but still could not view the info.  I'm very comfortable navigating through websites and I rarely find one that I just don't like but this is one.  If it wasn't for my kids wanting to do the bookfair and me not wanting to send cash....I would not use this website.  This website has the feel of being built, then needing to evolve and instead of updating the entire thing, it was just added on to....several times.  It's very piecemeal and not user friendly.  As for the next question about recommending the book club -- yes, I would recommend Scholastic Book Club but I would not recommend the website.

Please go back to the "old" system, as this is what parents and teachers are accustom to when placing an order.

column49: There is nowhere to use the "Class Code" I was provided by my child's teacher. Your FAQ does not mention the "Class Code", only how to register *without* it. Your registration form does not ask for the "Class Code". I tried searching by ZIP code and found my school, but my child's teacher does not show in the search results.     Also, the very first page of the website asks for a birthdate. I interpreted this to mean the website wanted my child's birthday but the website does not continue past the initial page if I use my child's birthday and it gives absolutely no feedback to the user as to what the problem is. (I did eventually figure out that it wanted MY birthday, but what use is my birthday to your site? Isn't it more useful to know the age of my child?)    I was excited to place an order from Scholastic out of nostalgia for my own book-ordering experiences as a kid but your site is a mess that has done little to encourage me to continue any further.

column49: My address was updated in our account to our physical address. WE have a PO box and we do not get mail at our physical address. When I got on live chat to ask for them to fix it I was told that maintenance could only fix it and they will be open monday between 8:00-3:00. I manage a classroom during this time.  My family are excited to get their books we have a $500 order to submit. Now they will have to wait until I can find the time to call and sit on hold while my children are left unsupervised. I can honestly say I'm considering not ever ordering from scholastic again!

column49: I am very dissatisfied with the changes made in the classroom ordering.  My school is a rural, low-income district.  Many of our families can't or won't take the time to navigate the online shopping.  In the past I would have parents that would send a set amount of cash ($5-10) and, as the teacher, I would help the child make their selections and complete their orders.    These families that will not go the extra steps to complete their orders online are the very famillies that need access to inexpensive books for their children the most.    This new process is very disappointing.

column49: I was kind of disappointed that it took extra steps now if we wanted to change the due date for our students to order. I understand it is one less step for the teachers however, when we get the magazines in to send out, I like to send it home right way. The due date that is set for the families was over a 2 week turn around and then another 5 days to submit.  I personally liked it better to be able to change it myself for a quicker turnaround time.     I did 'chat' with someone and they were VERY nice and helpful. However when I wanted to print the letter out, I couldn't change the date for that. So I had to copy the letter and paste it to email.  This takes more time on the teacher.

column49: I am very disappointed with the changes in the Scholastic Book Clubs this year.  I understand your desire to go digital, but I teach in a high poverty school district where not all families have access to the internet.  These families want to assist their children and have often purchased your one dollar and two-dollar books in the past.  Now these parents are not able to purchase books, because they either do not have internet access or the books are way too expensive for them.      I have always appreciated how Scholastic worked to assist children and their families in their reading adventure, but I am extremely disappointed with the changes and will probably not continue with these book clubs after this year.  The only reason I will continue this year is due to the fact that I have classroom book sponsors who have donated money to my classroom for books, and I will not disappoint their efforts in encouraging children to read.    Sincerely,  Rebecca Tripp  1st Grade Teacher

column49: I am unhappy that your flyers are no longer offering books at inexpensive prices. They seem to be filled with book sets and the students I have in my class do not have the money to be ordering such expensive items. I also have parents who do not use credit cards and are disappointed that they are no longer able to fill out a paper order form to give to me to submit. column49: I am very upset that you have eliminated the option to download labels, set our own due date and order for students. It is not very inclusive to assume it is easier for teachers to make everything digital, and to assume that all parents have access to online ordering. It does not in fact make my life easier to have to go and write all the due dates that are preselected on each flyer. I working a low income area and sometimes need to be flexible with dates in order to meet the families needs and pay schedules. As well, I have many that do not have online access, Unfortunately  I am not sure that I will use scholastic this year without such flexibility.  I don't know why we live in a world where we assume what is is easier and desirable for one is easier and desirable for all. I was very excited to receive our flyers and then spent way more time than necessary trying to navigate the website and figure things out. It wasn't until I used to chat feature I found all this out.

column49: Change is never easy, but I really don't like the way orders are done now. It is very limiting. No information in the flyers anymore. And I've brought up this issue that is never addressed. I am an urban school teacher. I buy most of the books. There are occasions where I will have some parents order for their child but the majority of my students over the years do not, so I make sure I supply my own library and I gift a lot of books. You have made it more difficult for our parents to order from you. Very few discounted books, and they would have to search online now and many of them can't.  I find it hard to believe I'm the only one bringing this up. I had zero orders this month and I anticipate that will be the norm for us from now on. And I have been ordering with you for many years teaching for the last 27.

column49: I was checking the website because I received an email stating my book order was on the way.  I hadn't placed my order yet so I wasn't sure what order was being shipped.  The parent online order was being shipped.  I'm glad Scholastic went ahead and shipped it.  I did plan on placing an order but the first of the year has been busier than usual.      I have to say I'm disappointed you are no longer offering the book coupons for teachers to purchase at a discount.  I usually misplace the coupons and finally find them when school is almost out.  However, I have always used the coupons to purchase books for the kids in my current classroom.    Another concern I have is the cost of the books.  I only had 1 family order books online.  This could be one of those classes where the families purchase their books through other methods. column49: I am totally confused by the new flyer design and also the website.    I live in a community where digital ordering is not easily accessible.  I am confused by the redesign of the new flyers because there is not the traditional order slip attatched.  Does that mean that orders are meant to only be done online by parents?    If not, where are parents to total their order so that they can know how much to send if ordering traditionally?  That seems like a lot of room for error, plus it would require more time on my part to add the total just to make sure that I don't owe someone change!  I am considering not ordering anything at all.  This just seems like it accentuates the haves and have nots social hierarchy that is already painfully present in this world.   I'm not strictly an old school person, but I do like some consistency that has been embedded by the traditional system that probably worked just fine.

column49: I'm really disappointed in the changes to Scholastic Book Clubs.  I was sad to find out the $1 books went away, now they are $2. I figured it was inflation and $2 books would still be a good deal, even though I would have liked to have known in June so I could have asked for more money when setting up my class campaign...I was surprised to see the change in being able to set due dates for my class. It feels like some teachers may have lapsed on orders, but we all got punished for that...The paper order looks fun with puzzles and mazes. However, the books prices have jumped. I will be surprised if I get many orders with books being $5-8. And not accepting cash orders! That takes away the opportunity from families who are trying to get by to send in a few dollars for a book. column49: I was not happy that I can not change my book order due date like I was able to in the past.  Having 3 weeks to submit an order is way too long for my PreK class.  I have found that the parents only need a week to get the orders back in or the forget all about it and never order.   I also prefer end of the month ordering so the children have the books during the following month.  With not being able to pick my own due date I am not able to do this.  I also didn't like that I couldn't pick the due date personally because the it gave me the 11th of October, well that is the first day back for us because the 9th is no school and we have a field trip on the 10th along with fall photos.  I would have never picked the 11th to add to that week.  I am sorry, I am just not a fan of that new aspect.  The time frame is too long for my group, I am sure it may work great to other grade levels or classes, but not mine.  The rest of the site seems great!

column49: For the past several years I have had volunteers donate $10 per student so that I can purchase a book per month for  the students in my classroom.  I always looked for the $1 deals, used teacher points and tried to buy value packs of books and I was always able to purchase at least 10 books for each student in my class. I started adding to my cart today to purchase books for September and October and  I am dumbfounded at the cost of books this year on Scholastic's book club site. Where are the $1 books? Why can't parents order through the classroom anymore? Why does something that was always so easy have to be so complicated?? I am frustrated  and regretting that I asked volunteers to help fund books this year. I have always been a huge fan of Scholastic and always sent home flyers and made ordering Scholastic books part of our classroom monthly routine. I will not be doing that this year.  Every colleague I've spoke to in my building feels the same. So disappointing.

column49: The site is not intuitive or helpful at all. It shows I'm in my class but won't let me connect to a teacher - says no teacher is participating for my school. I can't tell if I need to sign out - it looks like I need to, but I can't find where to do that.     I love the books Scholastic provides, but the interface is often super frustrating, and while the customer service reps are generally friendly, it's often hard to reach a real person. Getting anything other than the simplest question answered, whether by phone or online, is ridiculously difficult. Often the first answer I get to a written question has almost nothing to do with the question I ask.     Again, I love the books, the people I've interacted with try to be helpful, but the amount of time it takes to get a question answered or a problem solved almost makes it not worthwhile to work with Scholastic.

column49: Please bring back student orders, I was unaware that Scholastic had changed how student ordering works for teachers. Now, students must make their own orders at home. I serve a small rural community where most families do not have an internet connection at home. Before, students would bring in their 4-5-6 dollars, and I was able to place an order for them without having to worry about tax or exact change. Now that I can't enter student orders, I have to place the order as a teacher order and pay taxes for my students. This will be the LAST order I place. As an underpaid teacher unfortunately, I WILL NOT be footing a tax bill for my kiddos. I will also be informing the 50 teachers working at my school and 900+ teachers who work in our school district.

column49: I had updated my profile and requested catalogs for my new grade level at the start of the year. The October flyers were delivered today and I was given ones for the wrong grade level. When I went to the site for help, it kept directing me to the kids side of book clubs, with my previous bookmarks not being correct. I was already on the fence about continuing to use scholastic book clubs because of the barriers to accessing books for poor students and teachers, honestly. I used to use it so much more when shipping was cheaper, when there were $1 books in every flyer, when the $1 book store for teachers could be unlocked for the year instead of every month. We are a title one school, every child on our campus gets free lunch. There is a song on TikTok about scholastic being greedy and not caring about the kids. If you want that perception to change, that would be a good place to start.
